article.description:
Joy Cheek's putback with 1.2 seconds left lifted 
No. 17 Duke to a 51-49 victory over Pittsburgh on Saturday in the
 first game of the Maggie Dixon Classic
article.headline: Practice makes perfect as Cheek lands winning shot with 1.2 left
article.linkText: Duke's last-second drill pays off at Dixon Classic
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Duke spends a lot of practice time on late-game situations.

	   All that work paid off Saturday when Joy Cheek's putback with 
1.2 seconds left lifted Duke (No. 15 ESPN/USA Today, No. 17 AP) to a 51-49 victory over 
Pittsburgh in the first game of the Maggie Dixon Classic.

	   "We practice it a lot," Duke coach Joanne P. McCallie said. 
"I saw Joy following and I didn't know the clock, whether she got 
it in time."

	   Cheek scored 13 of her 16 points in the second half and Abby Waner added 10 for the Blue Devils (7-3).

	   "It was a great team win," Waner said. "Joy came up huge on that last play."

	   With 12.7 seconds left and the game tied at 49, the Blue Devils drove the 
length of the court and Chante Black missed a turnaround. Cheek got 
the rebound and put it in for the game-winner.

	   "We practice an 8-second drill where they always say the big's buddy should go after the ball. I was the buddy this time," Cheek 
said.

	 In the second game of the doubleheader -- the first women's doubleheader at Madison Square Garden in 26 years -- Rutgers (No. 3 ESPN/USA Today, No. 4 AP) faced Army. Scarlet Knights coach C. Vivian Stringer, irritated by the play of her team in a 49-44 loss to Duke on Thursday, benched her starters. Army built up a 19-15 lead before Stringer put in most of her starters, and Rutgers pulled away for the win, 59-42.


	   Shavonte Zellous and Jania Sims both scored 17 points for Pitt (6-3). The Panthers held a 24-18 lead with 6:20 left in the first 
half before going scoreless over the next nine minutes. Marcedes 
Walker finally ended the drought with a putback with 17:08 left in 
the second half.

	   "I don't know if it was good defense or they just missed shots, I'll have to watch the tape," McCallie said.

	   With Duke trailing 31-28, Cheek scored all seven points during a 
7-2 run that gave the Blue Devils a 35-33 lead.  The teams traded baskets before Duke used an 8-3 run, capped by 
Emily Waner's three-pointer as the shot clock expired, to take a 47-40 
lead with a little more than six minutes left.

	   Pitt responded with a 9-2 run to tie the game on Sims' layup with 1:13 left. With the game tied at 49, Sims stole the ball from Jasmine 
Thomas, but Zellous missed a jumper from the wing that would have 
given the Panthers the lead.

	   "You just got to make that shot," Pitt coach Agnus Berenato 
said. "I had a great day at work until that last 1.2 seconds. When 
you come as close as we did to beating a Top 25 team like Duke you 
have to seize it and we didn't today."

	   The inaugural Maggie Dixon Classic was played at West Point last 
year. Dixon died April 6, 2006 of arrhythmia, probably caused by an 
enlarged heart. Her death came three weeks after the completion of her first season 
as head coach at Army, a performance that won the admiration of 
the academy and all of college basketball.

	   Between the games, all four teams stood on the court during a
ceremony honoring Dixon, the late Army coach. Mayor Michael 
Bloomberg declared Saturday "Maggie Dixon Day" in New York City.

	   "Maggie set such a high standard in all that she did and we are 
so pleased to honor her by competing in such a fine event," 
McCallie said. "Women's basketball is greatly enriched by Maggie's 
legacy and this event allows all the participants to salute a 
respected and admired colleague."

	   A portion of the proceeds from the games will go to C.A.R.E 
(Cardiac Arrhythmias Research and Education Foundation, Inc.). 
C.A.R.E. offered free heart screenings for any child or teenager 
attending the Classic.
